>
  <p>Local search is a different game from organic SEO. When someone searches "plumber near me" or "best Italian restaurant in Manchester," Google uses an entirely separate set of ranking signals to determine which businesses appear in the map pack and local results. Your website is only one piece of the puzzle. Your Google Business Profile, citation consistency, review quantity and quality, and local relevance signals all feed into whether your business shows up when local customers are ready to buy.</p>

  <p>A local SEO audit examines every factor that influences your visibility in geographically targeted searches. It goes beyond your website to assess your entire local search presence across Google, directory listings, review platforms, and competitor positioning. For businesses that depend on local customers — which includes the vast majority of service businesses, retail shops, restaurants, and professional services firms — this audit directly determines how many enquiries and walk-ins you receive.</p>

  <h2 id="what-is-a-local-seo-audit">What Is a Local SEO Audit</h2>

  <p>A local SEO audit is a systematic review of every factor that affects your business's visibility in local search results. Unlike a standard website SEO audit that focuses primarily on your domain, a local audit must evaluate assets and signals that exist outside your website entirely.</p>

  <p>The audit covers three interconnected areas. First, your Google Business Profile — the listing that appears in map packs, Google Maps, and the knowledge panel. This profile often drives more phone calls and direction requests than your website does. Second, your off-site presence — directory listings, citations, review platforms, and social profiles that collectively validate your business's name, address, phone number, and legitimacy. Third, your website's local relevance — how well your on-site content, schema markup, and technical setup support local ranking signals.</p>

  <p>Most businesses dramatically underinvest in the first two areas. They spend months optimising their website for keywords while their Google Business Profile has an incorrect phone number, their Yelp listing shows an old address, and their only reviews are three years old. A local SEO audit identifies exactly where these gaps exist and prioritises fixes by their impact on local visibility.</p>

  <p>The businesses that dominate local search are not always the ones with the best websites. They are the ones with the most complete, consistent, and actively managed local search presence. This audit ensures you are competing on all the factors that actually matter.</p>

  <h2 id="google-business-profile-check">Google Business Profile Check</h2>

  <p>Your Google Business Profile (GBP) is the single most influential asset for local search visibility. It controls what appears in the map pack, the knowledge panel, and Google Maps. An incomplete or inaccurate profile is equivalent to having no storefront sign — customers who are actively looking for your service will walk right past.</p>

  <p>Audit your GBP against every available field:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Business name accuracy</strong> — your GBP name must match your real-world business name exactly. Do not stuff keywords into the business name (e.g., "Smith Plumbing - Emergency Plumber London 24/7"). Google's guidelines prohibit this, and competitors will report it. Check that your name matches your signage, business registration, and website.</li>
    <li><strong>Primary and secondary categories</strong> — your primary category is the strongest local ranking signal you control. Verify it matches the service or product your customers search for most. Add relevant secondary categories for additional services. Check what categories your top-ranking competitors use and ensure you are not missing any that apply to your business.</li>
    <li><strong>Business description</strong> — fill the 750-character description with a clear, keyword-natural explanation of what your business does, who you serve, and what areas you cover. This content does not directly affect rankings but influences click-through rates from the knowledge panel.</li>
    <li><strong>Photos and media</strong> — GBP listings with more than 100 photos receive 520% more calls than the average listing, according to BrightLocal research. Upload high-quality photos of your premises, team, products, and completed work. Add new photos at least monthly to signal an active, operating business.</li>
    <li><strong>Service areas and address</strong> — if you serve customers at your location, your address must be verified and accurate. If you are a service-area business that visits customers, define your service areas precisely. Do not set a service area radius larger than you actually serve — it dilutes your relevance for searches in your core area.</li>
    <li><strong>Hours of operation</strong> — verify that regular hours, special hours, and holiday hours are all correct. Incorrect hours lead to customers arriving at a closed business, resulting in negative reviews and lost trust.</li>
    <li><strong>Attributes</strong> — complete every applicable attribute (wheelchair accessible, free Wi-Fi, LGBTQ+ friendly, appointment required, etc.). Attributes appear in your listing and can be used as filters in Google Maps.</li>
    <li><strong>Products and services</strong> — add your products or services with descriptions and prices. This content appears directly in your GBP listing and gives potential customers a reason to choose you before clicking through to your website.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="nap-consistency-audit">NAP Consistency Audit</h2>

  <p>NAP stands for Name, Address, Phone number — the three pieces of information that search engines use to verify your business exists and is located where you say it is. Inconsistencies in your NAP across the web send conflicting signals that reduce Google's confidence in your business information and lower your local rankings.</p>

  <p>NAP inconsistencies are more common than most businesses realise. An office move three years ago might have updated the website and GBP but left the old address on 40 directory listings. A phone number change could mean the number on Yell.com differs from the one on your website. Even small variations — "St" versus "Street," "Suite 100" versus "Ste 100" — can be treated as inconsistencies by citation matching algorithms.</p>

  <p>Conduct your NAP audit in three steps:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Define your canonical NAP</strong> — establish the exact business name, address, and phone number that should appear everywhere. Write it down exactly as it should appear, including punctuation, abbreviations, and formatting. This becomes your reference standard.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit your owned properties</strong> — check your website (header, footer, contact page, about page), Google Business Profile, social media profiles (Facebook, LinkedIn, Twitter, Instagram), and any apps or third-party platforms where you have direct control. Every instance must match your canonical NAP exactly.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit third-party citations</strong> — search for your business name in Google, Bing, and across major directories. Check Yell, Thomson Local, Yelp, TripAdvisor (if applicable), industry-specific directories, local chambers of commerce, and any other platforms where your business appears. Catalogue every inconsistency.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Use a tool like BrightLocal, Moz Local, or Whitespark to automate the citation discovery process. These tools scan hundreds of directories simultaneously and flag inconsistencies, saving hours of manual checking. The investment is worth it — NAP consistency is one of the most actionable local ranking factors, and fixing inconsistencies delivers measurable ranking improvements within weeks.</p>

  <h2 id="local-landing-pages">Local Landing Pages</h2>

  <p>If your business serves multiple areas, your website needs dedicated landing pages for each area. These pages should target location-specific keywords ("plumber in Reading," "accountant Slough") and provide genuinely useful information about your services in that area. The key word is genuine — Google's guidelines explicitly penalise thin, duplicated location pages that simply swap out the city name while keeping everything else identical.</p>

  <p>Audit your existing local landing pages against these criteria:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unique content per page</strong> — each location page must contain unique content that is specific to that area. Reference local landmarks, mention area-specific service considerations, include testimonials from customers in that area, and provide directions or travel information. A page that reads identically to your other location pages except for the city name in the heading is doorway page content and risks a manual penalty.</li>
    <li><strong>Title and meta structure</strong> — each location page should target "[Service] in [Location]" or "[Location] [Service]" in the title tag. The meta description should mention the specific area and include a call to action relevant to local customers.</li>
    <li><strong>Internal linking</strong> — location pages should link to your main service pages and to adjacent location pages where relevant. They should be linked from your site navigation, footer, or a dedicated "areas we serve" hub page — not hidden in the body text of a blog post.</li>
    <li><strong>Contact information</strong> — each location page should include the relevant contact information for that area, whether it is a local phone number, a specific office address, or a booking link filtered to that location.</li>
    <li><strong>Map embed</strong> — include a Google Map embed showing your service area or office location for each area page. This reinforces geographic relevance and provides a useful visual reference for potential customers.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If you serve a large number of areas, prioritise creating pages for your highest-value locations first. Better to have 10 excellent local pages than 50 thin ones. You can expand the coverage over time as each page earns traffic and validates the approach.</p>

  <h2 id="review-strategy-audit">Review Strategy Audit</h2>

  <p>Reviews influence local rankings, click-through rates from map pack listings, and conversion rates once customers land on your page. Google has confirmed that review quantity, quality, and recency are local ranking factors. Beyond the algorithm, reviews are the primary trust signal for potential customers evaluating your business against competitors.</p>

  <p>Your review audit should assess:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Total review count</strong> — compare your review count on Google against your top three map pack competitors. If they have 150 reviews and you have 30, you face a significant disadvantage. Calculate the gap and determine how many reviews per month you need to close it within a reasonable timeframe.</li>
    <li><strong>Average rating</strong> — a 4.0+ rating is the minimum threshold for consumer trust. Below 4.0, click-through rates drop significantly. If your rating is below 4.0, audit your recent negative reviews for patterns that indicate operational issues worth addressing.</li>
    <li><strong>Review recency</strong> — a business with 200 reviews but none in the last three months sends a signal of decline. Google weights recent reviews more heavily. You need a steady flow of new reviews, not a burst followed by silence.</li>
    <li><strong>Review responses</strong> — check whether you respond to every review, both positive and negative. Responding to reviews signals active management and can positively influence potential customers reading reviews. Google's own documentation recommends responding to reviews.</li>
    <li><strong>Review platforms beyond Google</strong> — check your presence on Trustpilot, Facebook, Yelp, and industry-specific review sites. While Google reviews carry the most weight for map pack rankings, reviews on other platforms contribute to your overall online reputation and may appear in standard organic results.</li>
    <li><strong>Review generation process</strong> — assess whether you have a systematic process for requesting reviews from satisfied customers. The businesses with the most reviews are not necessarily the best — they are the ones that consistently ask. Audit whether you have automated review request emails, follow-up SMS messages, or in-person prompts built into your customer journey.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="citation-audit">Citation Audit</h2>

  <p>Citations are mentions of your business name, address, and phone number on external websites. They come in two forms: structured citations (directory listings with formatted business data) and unstructured citations (mentions in blog posts, news articles, or social media). Both types contribute to your local search authority.</p>

  <p>Your citation audit should cover:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Core directory presence</strong> — verify that your business is listed on the essential UK directories: Google Business Profile, Bing Places, Apple Maps, Yell.com, Thomson Local, Yelp UK, Facebook, and LinkedIn. Missing listings represent easy wins — each one takes minutes to claim and contributes to your citation count.</li>
    <li><strong>Industry-specific directories</strong> — identify the top directories for your industry and check your presence. For example, TripAdvisor for hospitality, Checkatrade or Bark for trades, Avvo for legal, Healthgrades for medical. These industry directories often carry more weight than general directories because they demonstrate niche relevance.</li>
    <li><strong>Duplicate listings</strong> — search for duplicate listings of your business on each directory. Duplicates split your review count, create NAP inconsistencies, and confuse both users and search engines. Merge or delete duplicates wherever the platform allows it.</li>
    <li><strong>Competitor citation gap</strong> — use a tool like Whitespark's citation finder to discover where your competitors are listed that you are not. These represent opportunities to match and exceed their citation profile.</li>
    <li><strong>Citation quality</strong> — not all citations carry equal weight. A listing on a high-authority, well-maintained directory is worth more than dozens of listings on spam directories. Focus your efforts on quality directories with real traffic and proper editorial standards.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="local-schema-markup">Local Schema Markup</h2>

  <p>LocalBusiness schema markup tells search engines exactly what your business is, where it is located, when it is open, and how customers can reach you. This structured data bridges the gap between your website content and the machine-readable format that search engines use to populate knowledge panels, map results, and rich snippets.</p>

  <p>Your schema audit should verify these elements on your homepage and contact page at minimum:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>LocalBusiness type specificity</strong> — use the most specific Schema.org type that applies. Instead of generic "LocalBusiness," use "Plumber," "Restaurant," "LegalService," "Dentist," or whatever subtype matches your business. Specificity helps Google understand exactly what you do.</li>
    <li><strong>Complete address markup</strong> — include streetAddress, addressLocality, addressRegion, postalCode, and addressCountry as separate fields within the PostalAddress object. This granularity helps Google match your business to specific geographic queries.</li>
    <li><strong>Opening hours</strong> — mark up your hours using the OpeningHoursSpecification type. Include special hours for holidays. This data can appear directly in search results and voice search answers.</li>
    <li><strong>GeoCoordinates</strong> — include latitude and longitude coordinates for your business location. This geo-data reinforces your geographic positioning in local algorithms.</li>
    <li><strong>AggregateRating</strong> — if you display reviews on your website, mark them up with AggregateRating schema. Note that the reviews must be genuine, displayed on the page, and not self-serving. Marking up fabricated reviews violates Google's guidelines and can result in manual actions.</li>
    <li><strong>SameAs references</strong> — include sameAs properties linking to your Google Business Profile, social media profiles, and directory listings. This helps search engines connect your various online presences as belonging to the same entity.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Validate your schema using Google's Rich Results Test and check Search Console for any structured data errors. Even small formatting issues — a missing closing bracket, an incorrect data type — can invalidate your entire schema block.</p>

  <h2 id="competitor-local-analysis">Competitor Local Analysis</h2>

  <p>The final component of a local SEO audit is understanding your competitive landscape. Local search is a zero-sum game — there are only three spots in the map pack, and every business ranking above you is one you need to outperform across the factors Google uses for local rankings.</p>

  <p>Analyse your top five local competitors across these dimensions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>GBP completeness comparison</strong> — review each competitor's Google Business Profile. Note their categories, photo count, review count and average rating, posting frequency, and how completely they have filled out their profile. Identify areas where you can match or exceed their profile completeness.</li>
    <li><strong>Review velocity</strong> — track how many new reviews each competitor receives per month. This tells you the pace you need to maintain to close the review gap. If a competitor gains 15 reviews per month and you gain 3, the gap will widen even if you are improving.</li>
    <li><strong>Citation profile</strong> — use Whitespark or BrightLocal to compare your citation count and quality against competitors. Identify directories where competitors are listed that you are not, and prioritise claiming those listings.</li>
    <li><strong>Website local signals</strong> — review competitor websites for local content quality. Do they have detailed service area pages? Do they publish local blog content? Is their schema markup more complete than yours? These observations reveal the content investment required to compete.</li>
    <li><strong>Backlink comparison</strong> — local backlinks from regional news sites, local business associations, community organisations, and event sponsorships carry particular weight in local search. Use Ahrefs or Semrush to identify local backlinks your competitors have earned and develop a strategy to earn similar links.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Document your competitive analysis in a comparison matrix with your business and your top competitors as columns, and each ranking factor as a row. This visual comparison makes it immediately clear where you are strong, where you are weak, and where the highest-impact improvements lie. Update this matrix quarterly to track your progress and monitor competitor movements.</p>
